    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_449101266" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/449101266" />
    <a title="John Lucy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5413762-john-lucy"><img alt="John Lucy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1394206318p2/5413762.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/449101266?book_show_action=true">Nov 05, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John Lucy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John Lucy" href="/user/show/5413762-john-lucy">John Lucy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer449101266" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15487083714829663447">The only reason I picked up this book was that I got it from my grandmother&apos;s library. At the time my edition was printed, Hersey had not yet won the Pulitzer Prize for this novel, so I had no reason to think it was any good. Indeed, for the first few chapters I wondered if reading A Bell for Adano would be a total waste of my time: I thought the beginning of the story seemed forced, especially because the description of characters (Borth, for instance, is described as a &quot;wise guy&quot;) didn&apos;t match</span>
  <span id="freeText15487083714829663447" style="display:none">The only reason I picked up this book was that I got it from my grandmother's library. At the time my edition was printed, Hersey had not yet won the Pulitzer Prize for this novel, so I had no reason to think it was any good. Indeed, for the first few chapters I wondered if reading A Bell for Adano would be a total waste of my time: I thought the beginning of the story seemed forced, especially because the description of characters (Borth, for instance, is described as a "wise guy") didn't match with their behavior. <br /><br />Around page 50 I changed my mind. This is, I believe, Hersey's first book; and, if I'm not mistaken, he wrote it in three weeks. With that said, I can understand if in the first few chapters, which are not very long, Hersey was still trying to hit his stride. By chapter seven or eight the story is smooth as butter. Memorable characters, with plenty of humor (intentional humor on Hersey's part, unintentional on the part of the characters), and memorable events, again with plenty of intentional/unintentional humor. Every character, even the "bad guy" General Marvin, have a particular charm. Major Joppolo, the main character, and his relationships with Captain Purvis and Zito, the town usher, are perhaps the most hilarious and enjoyable.<br /><br />Hersey's style in a way fits the wise guy Sergeant Borth, who sees World War II as a big joke and thinks everyone needs to calm down some, the best. While Hersey treats his subject matter seriously and tries showing the reader, in story form, that wars cannot be won only with a mighty military, Hersey infuses his seriousness with a lightness that cannot only be described as funny. With every word Hersey hits the right tone. Plus, let's not underestimate the power of short chapters. A Bell for Adano is very easy to read.<br /><br />What adds to the quality of this book is that it's not an anti-war nor a pro-war war novel. It's just a war story about a major trying to take care of an Italian occupied town. If anything the book is a call for more compassion and caring and thoughtfulness toward one another. I can jump on that boat, for sure.<br /><br />I highly recommend this. The book is so good that you might remember it forty years later. My father, for instance, who has a terrible memory and often has to read a book or watch a movie halfway to recollect if he had read or seen it before; with this book, however, he saw it in my lap and immediately said, "That's the one about the Italian town, right?... Yeah, I remember reading that when I was much younger, not even your age yet." He's 60, I'm 25. That means his awful memory survived at least 35 years. It's a good book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15487083714829663447" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

