<div id="review_405977720" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/405977720" />
    <a title="Aubrey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey"><img alt="Aubrey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1472535045p2/4119460.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/405977720?book_show_action=true">Jul 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aubrey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aubrey" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey">Aubrey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=1-read-on-hand">1-read-on-hand</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=r-goodreads">r-goodreads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=ccb-2021">ccb-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=r-2021">r-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=2021-challenges">2021-challenges</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=1-star">1-star</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer405977720" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9395883238352222444">For several years now, I&apos;ve participated in reading challenges that largely center around works that are commonly called &quot;classics,&quot; some earning the title fair and square, others slapped up on the higher echelons of the ivory tower simply because that&apos;s what the academics of yesteryear did before. The problem with doing so when you have my reading sensibilities is that of running a high risk of reading a work simply because it fits a certain genre and happens to be by a woman and/or person of c</span>
  <span id="freeText9395883238352222444" style="display:none">For several years now, I've participated in reading challenges that largely center around works that are commonly called "classics," some earning the title fair and square, others slapped up on the higher echelons of the ivory tower simply because that's what the academics of yesteryear did before. The problem with doing so when you have my reading sensibilities is that of running a high risk of reading a work simply because it fits a certain genre and happens to be by a woman and/or person of color, an endeavor that becomes increasingly foolish when one's hundreds of white boy works languish in a limbo of almost but not quite banishment and, more importantly taking up all of one's storage space. So, this year, I decided to make things a tad easier for myself by drawing upon my full library of resources, but in exchange doubling upon on certain categories when it was feasible to fit a non-white boy work in with a more status quo companion. Thus, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11702.The_Labyrinth_of_Solitude_and_Other_Writings" title="The Labyrinth of Solitude and Other Writings by Octavio Paz" rel="nofollow noopener">The Labyrinth of Solitude and Other Writings</a> was paired with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4406.East_of_Eden" title="East of Eden by John Steinbeck" rel="nofollow noopener">East of Eden</a> for Nobel Laureate for Lit, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/22237161.The_Sellout" title="The Sellout by Paul Beatty" rel="nofollow noopener">The Sellout</a> with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/139087.The_Line_of_Beauty" title="The Line of Beauty by Alan Hollinghurst" rel="nofollow noopener">The Line of Beauty</a> for the Booker, and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23168277.The_Sympathizer" title="The Sympathizer by Viet Thanh Nguyen" rel="nofollow noopener">The Sympathizer</a> with this for the Pulitzer. It's not as if I always liked the more interesting selection better than its more conforming counterpart, but when it comes to a work such as this, I have to wonder at how sunk I must have been in the establishment to add something like this without much hesitance. It's one of those times where all one can say is, well. At least it was short.<br /><br />Hersey is a name I caught a glimpse of via a work called 'Hiroshima' that I saw being carried around as required reading by high school students who had a different English teacher than I did. It was that memory that gave me increasing misgivings whenever I looked at this particular work on my shelves and contemplated finally getting to it, for white people as a whole are, even today, extremely bad at writing about Japanese people in terms not almost entirely composed of lascivious drool and exotifying nonsense, and Hersey's much lauded work of reportage is coming up on its eightieth anniversary. Now, one would be forgiven in thinking that, since this particular piece here is both a piece of fiction and is only concerned with white people (save for when the stereotype of Black rapists in the US army is propagated for the sake of a sensationalized plot point and the city of Algiers is acknowledged to be a real place if only for the stationing of WASP soldiers), there's less of a chance for the author to come off as a massive twat. Unfortunately, that involves vastly underestimating the human penchant for dehumanizingly hiearchicalizing, as well as overestimating how capable certain kinds of writers need to be when it comes to writing human beings in order to win a major literary prize for it. As such, the name of the game for this work is choking amounts of <i>sentiment</i>, whether it be considering the kid at fault for being killed in a hit and run by US soldiers, feeling oh so sowwy for the poor widdle flirtatious US soldier with a wife back home because he's not as rapacious as his cohort, and having a weirdly solemn fetish for blonde hair. All this work needed was a couple of songs and some more anthropomorphic animations and it would be a prime example of some of the uglier pieces of musically inclined propaganda that I'm sure Disney has been hard at work scrubbing every trace of off the face of every obscure corner of the Internet. "Aged badly" and all that, but honestly, it really didn't take long for it to "age badly", especially in the reading circles of the real world, rather than the artificial ones propped up for the sake of certain folks' sense of personal esteem. Criticize the Internet all you will, but you have to admit, it's made it a lot harder for this kind of severe myopia to propagate itself throughout the decades under the title of "quality literature".<br /><br />This is probably the most severe reading disappointment I've had so far this year, but to be honest, part of me saw it coming. I'm already not the best fit for 'humorous' or 'touching' in the standard definitions of the words in written media, and a work that's all "ohr gawsh gee whiz" while simultaneously being a contemptuous little pissant in regards to 90% of the world's population is more pathetic than anything else. Perhaps this piece wouldn't have done quite so badly in my estimation had I not gotten through the entirety of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/51799.The_Decameron" title="The Decameron by Giovanni Boccaccio" rel="nofollow noopener">The Decameron</a> last month and even appreciated it for the most part, but I simply have no tolerance for patronizing bad faith these days, so this work probably still would've rubbed me wrong even without having recently experienced a monumental piece of literature that was being read and enjoyed before WASP precursors to the US nation had even figured out how to build boats sturdy enough to cross the Atlantic. I'm not saying that only the old stuff is worth reading and everything published after the 19th century isn't worth the plastic wrap that it came packaged in. I simply don't think that this is a work that would have survived as well as it has without having some deeply engrained status quo crutches at its disposal, and in the age of the great de-centering of the usual taken for granted centers, I don't see it lasting long.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9395883238352222444" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

